December also marks the end of the fall semester, a time when everyone is busy with schoolwork and grading. Filling out the commuter log might have gotten lost in the shuffle. Plus, December brings the holiday season, often resulting in a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January for the spring semester, which might have contributed to the low log submissions for that month. However, February's low submissions remain unexplained. The project might just have experienced an initial burst of energy that naturally faded. To boost engagement, we organized the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did indeed increase log submissions. This highlights the challenge of maintaining project momentum during natural engagement dips and holiday/semester breaks. Another hurdle for this project, or any similar initiative, is the deeply ingrained culture of driving personal cars for commuting. To encourage alternative commuting, we offered gift certificates to local businesses like restaurants, coffee shops, a bookstore, and even national chains. It would have been interesting to see the impact of larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars. If we had gradually increased the prize value over time, it might have boosted participation and engagement. The gift cards were effective at the start, but announcing larger prizes in December and January could have sustained and possibly even increased participation.

Another financial tool to consider is an ETF, or exchange-traded fund. Unlike index funds, ETFs offer more flexibility and trade like individual stocks on an exchange. They bring the diversification of an index fund and the perks of owning a single stock, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share. The advantages are clear, but so are some drawbacks. Like stocks, ETFs charge commissions on trades, and while their expense ratios are lower than mutual funds, they can still add up.

A savvy investor should assess whether the benefits of owning an ETF, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent. For this effort, let's examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's total assets. The top 10 holdings are listed below along with their respective percentages.

To gauge how well these top 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, let's calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, normalized to 100%. The results of these calculations are shown in the chart below.

The chart shows that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings yields a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF as a whole. Initially, it seems a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower Beta. However, the statistical significance of these portfolios may not be different.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

Another one of Edgar Allan Poe's notable works is "Dream-Land," which he himself considered one of his better poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which, according to Mabbott, traces back to Virgil's writings. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While it is certain that Virgil did use the term, there is a more contemporary source to which credit may also be given. Poe had a keen interest in German authors, especially the works of Goethe.

This is significant because it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," discusses the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was likely influenced by Goethe's work.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated writer, particularly known for his poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second in the year of his death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust, there is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." This poem tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet as a gift. After her death, the king becomes consumed with drinking and grief, ultimately deciding to end his life. He gives away all his possessions to his children, except for the goblet, which he throws into the sea before deleting himself from the cliff. The descriptions of the King of Thule and the speaker in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, suggesting a dark reflection of Poe's own experiences and struggles with substance abuse.

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works. He uses the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but he also employs the term "Thule" as bookends for "Dream-Land." "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule, which is dark, lonely, and haunted by the memory of dead friends. The lack of color in the world mirrors the gloom of the King of Thule's situation after the loss of his wife. The entire poem is as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a significant author whose work Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his admiration for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe expressed that, aside from their connection, he would have been exposed to Goethe's work through numerous reproductions of his original publications.

In the case of Jennifer Palmer suing D&D Markets, California law may allow her to seek punitive damages if she can prove the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with malicious intent. Palmer needs to show that Martin was aware of the potential harm from the applesauce spill and deliberately disregarded it. Martin was informed about the spill twice, but he failed to have it cleaned for a half-hour because he was eating dinner. This could be considered malicious if he knew the previous incidents involving slip-and-fall injuries and chose not to act. Palmer's claim that Martin's actions were despicable is weaker but still reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009.

CBC was the place where I first delved into the teachings of Islam, four years ago now. The heated debates sparked in class about whether or not Islam is inherently hostile were as relevant then as they are today, perhaps even more so. Since 9/11, I've witnessed the media's view of Islam shifting from outright hostility towards extremists to an almost extreme tolerance. I doubt that, back in 2001, an American presidential candidate with an obvious Muslim background like Barack Obama could have been a possibility.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography has always intrigued me, as it seems to present a stark contrast to the historical accounts I've read. According to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a martyr and a humble figure who, rather than forcibly converting others, saw people come to him seeking the truth in his teachings. This depiction, however, doesn't align with the historical narrative of Muhammad's rise to power. It's as if the biography is trying to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, portraying him as wise, gentle, and humble. Yet, history contradicts this, and I can't help but wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true historical context surrounding Muhammad's rise.

Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad that intrigue me. For instance, the story of Muhammad multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men bears a striking resemblance to Jesus' miracle of feeding the five thousand. This style of writing, I believe, is an attempt to portray Muhammad as a humble prophet who, through his actions and teachings, demonstrates the truth without needing to prove anything. This approach, however, diminishes the life and miracles of Jesus, making it seem like they are borrowing credit from his life.

The biography also includes numerous stories that aim to provide 'witnesses' to the conversion of people to Islam. However, many of these tales are told from a third-party perspective, such as the author hearing the story from someone who heard it from another person. I found this approach to be less convincing, as it often diminishes the stories' credibility by adding layers of uncertainty. It's as if the authors were trying to build a case for the truth of the stories, but the third-party nature of many of them makes it seem more like a string of hearsay.

What troubles me the most about this work is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, and wise figure. This portrayal contradicts historical accounts of Muhammad's rise to power and makes me question whether modern Muslims are aware of the historical context surrounding his life.

So, the teachings of Jesus, the beliefs he held during his lifetime, were quickly left behind as Christianity evolved after his passing. Looking at this from a broad perspective, it's clear that Christianity has drifted further and further from its origins over time. Today, we see a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditional people persist and may resist any new thinking, they might not be enough to influence the entire population. Among believers, a historical awareness will undoubtedly grow in future years. There will be a longing to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from what Jesus originally intended. It may take decades or even centuries, but the end result will be inevitable: a return to the religion's original form. A movement will emerge, growing in numbers, and will peel away layers of doctrine, one by one, like a clock winding backward. When this trend reaches the United States and Europe, it will influence many to worship as if they were living during Jesus' time, following only his ideas. The church, as an institution, will remain strong to guide this path. However, as the theological clock reverses, the extreme diversity within Christendom will reduce to greater uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions, we'll see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with such reversals. For example, Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, but the empire later became a Christian institution. Our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal coming in the future will play out in the realm of Christianity, undoing history and diversity in the process. A key part of what will enable this process is interpreting Jesus' words as metaphorical, rather than literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime?
       If we delve deep into history, we find that Judaism was the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the belief in a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at the core of the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not unified in spirit, dividing into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots, along with a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" illustrates how, deep down, humans are inherently selfish and focused solely on their own prosperity. They strive to make their lives as comfortable and successful as possible, without considering the well-being of those less fortunate. This is evident in the owners and managers of the massive factories, who are solely driven by the desire to expand their enterprises, often at the expense of others. They disregard any collateral damage caused by their relentless pursuit of growth. Upton Sinclair vividly portrays this with his description, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery highlights the environmental devastation and the callous disregard for all life forms affected by the factories. The owners and managers also prioritize profits over their employees' welfare, subjecting them to grueling work conditions without any concern for their well-being or safety. They exploit their workers, often firing them without notice or compensation, as there were few regulations or protections for labor in that era. Sinclair's portrayal of the workers as "slaves" underscores the inhuman treatment they endured, with no recourse or support systems in place. Even when unions were formed, they often worsened the situation by exploiting the workers themselves. The unchecked power of the owners and managers, combined with the desperation of the workers, resulted in a system that was as oppressive and exploitative as chattel slavery.

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes towards significant topics. Some techniques work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes many of these methods in his novel "The Great Gatsby." One approach he often uses is combining an adjective and a noun that don't typically go together to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Another technique is investing meaning in symbols and using them repeatedly for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs the latter technique with several colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel, Fitzgerald assigns meanings to colors like white/gray and red/pink, and later uses these meanings to reinforce a particular feeling around important objects.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher, more refined status, and gray signifying age and decay. He establishes this meaning early in the novel by frequently using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as “in white” (8), and even Nick wears “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party. Tom is in a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). The only time people aren’t wearing white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald also uses these colors to depict common, unimportant subjects: as Nick heads to work, he descends “the white chasms of lower New York” (56), and the names of people at Gatsby’s parties become “gray names” (61) on his schedule. Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses” (28), and plain or common people and places are described as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy shared a “white girlhood” (19), there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).

After imbuing these colors with meaning, Fitzgerald uses them to symbolize unimportance or uniformity in subjects. This technique begins with Daisy. After a long period with little significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster” (74); readers start to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform, something that Gatsby desires and yearns for. Fitzgerald employs this method often to emphasize Daisy’s uniformity, such as with a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her wearing “white” (115) before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

Another thing I've been doing is researching the land around San Diego. It's got a great climate for farming, so it's no surprise that it's super productive. You can find all sorts of stuff there like tomatoes, citrus fruits, and all sorts of greens. There's a big market for organic produce too, with many local supporters lined up. Plus, they do tours and let you enjoy the outdoors. Sounds like a sweet deal, right? But it's not all sunshine and roses. Organic farming can be pricey because you've got to put in extra work to keep things pest-free and healthy without using chemicals. And the land I found on a real estate website? It's a big piece of chaparral, grassland, and oak forest next to a national forest. It's home to some rare critters, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. There's a conservation plan for the area that's still being worked on, but it's got over a hundred species on the list. The land has a history too - it was used by Native Americans and later by cattle ranchers. I'm looking into government programs to see if I can get some help to make the farm more profitable and wildlife-friendly.

Culture plays a significant part in any negotiation. Culture is more about what it isn't than what it is, and its significance can vary greatly. It's not one-size-fits-all, and generalizations like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are too broad and oversimplified. While understanding general cultural traits is helpful, it's more important to grasp how a culture's attitudes and values impact negotiations and how to adapt to them. When encountering a foreign culture, one tends to relate it to their own, making comparisons inevitable. Understanding a foreign culture or mindset can involve delving into its history and recognizing its prejudices. Instead of judging or trying to change a culture, one should simply accept it and work within its parameters, especially if you're at a weaker bargaining position. If you're in a "foreign" environment, respecting local traditions and beliefs can help overcome cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It's also crucial to note that culture isn't just about national or international differences. Within a single nation, many companies have their own corporate cultures. These can vary widely, with some emphasizing long hours, while others foster a more relaxed work schedule. You can see these differences in employee dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy at any level, while others limit it to "company-approved" causes. Even within the U.S., corporate cultures can vary greatly, from region to region and from urban to suburban environments. Some cultures may appear more uniform to outsiders, but it's essential to look deeper.

Values are particularly important to understand because they explain why a culture is the way it is. If saving face or communal harmony is valued in a culture, a negotiator won't publicly shame their company or superiors to succeed. Conversely, a negotiator from a culture that prioritizes a hard-driven bargain won't rush to settle. It's crucial to consider these generalizations before sitting down at the table, but also to learn something about your opponent's personal background to make the negotiation more effective.

The fool hath said in his heart, "There is no God." This quote, found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, is the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about the existence of God. Interestingly, this sentiment is shared by another author we'll discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Both of their arguments aim to prove the existence of the same concept of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To simplify, we must assume they both believe in this God. However, neither truly provides a complete basis for belief in God.

Let's first look at St. Anselm's argument. He suggests that understanding God comes from within our own hearts. He argues that since God exists within our understanding, we cannot conceive of his non-existence. This concept, although worded convolutedly, basically means that proof for God lies within our own minds. We don't need to search beyond our inner selves for evidence; the truth about God is found by exploring what we inherently know. This idea is often called faith within Christian literature.

In contrast, St. Thomas Aquinas believes that God's existence can be proven through logic and empirical evidence, without relying on faith. Such a stance is advantageous for converting new believers, as it allows for recruitment without needing people to accept unprovable concepts. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support this claim: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He shows that the proof of God's existence lies in the logical necessity for him. If you know you're missing a puzzle piece, you can deduce the features and existence of the missing piece without seeing it.

Sometime around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a future Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned the world and attained enlightenment, leading to the birth of Buddhism—with the most traditional sect being Theravada Buddhism. The religion is nearly twenty-five hundred years old, and it has evolved significantly from its original form. This can be seen in Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. Monks and laypeople alike take part, despite Buddha never having taught about such a ritual. These changes range from superficial traditions to the religion's core beliefs. Both monastic and lay Theravada Buddhists have had to adjust their doctrinal principles over time, due to both internal and external influences, both friendly and hostile.

This discussion will use several key terms. Internal forces are those that originate from within the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. External forces are those from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, born of a negative perception of Buddhism. Benign forces are those that don't intend to harm or help, but may do so as a side effect. These terms will be used frequently in this discussion.

To understand the religion, we must first explore its core doctrines. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is made up of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka includes all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka sets out rules for life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka deals with the religion's metaphysical components. These include concepts like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering, and Anicca—impermanence. Only by accepting these ideas can one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and overcome lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion. The Vinaya Pitaka contains rules for life, such as the five precepts for laypeople and many more for monks. The most fundamental principle of Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico once shared a long-standing rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. Diehl and Goerts (2000, p. 145) describe this rivalry, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 being its peak. During this conflict, the United States attacked and won, gaining Texas and the American Southwest. The rivalry was fueled by differences in religion, culture, and tradition, as well as a clash of material interests (Schmitt, 1974, p. 30-31). This isn't uncommon among neighboring nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Mexico and Cuba, being geographically close to the United States, have historically been rivals, unlike other Latin American nations that have maintained good relations with the United States. Religious differences, similar to the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union, played a significant role in this rivalry. Sally Frahm (2001) states, “If in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p. 86). The distrust between the English and Spanish, a legacy from colonial times, further strained relations. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes during this 57-year period, most of which were territorial issues involving border raids and frontier problems. Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry's decline began when Mexico became more dependent on the United States, and it ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th century (p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly struck down by an illness that I had never known existed.

At the time, I was a nurse. I had chosen this profession due to a deep-seated need for the safety and security that I had lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I grew older. Thus, even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist, perhaps a mix of both, I chose nursing.

Now, here I am, 46 years old, single, and without much money in the bank, unable to work. I am still disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have virtually nothing left that I can call my own. I manage to get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet, there is one thing I know for certain. I could not have made it through all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And let me tell you, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel very strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life, big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to overcome on your own.

I concur wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's "basket"; Lord knows it is moldy and falling apart, anyway. Yet, I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help, rather than having each of us individually scrambling out to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism; it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and an array of batteries, candles, and waterproof matches, as well as canned goods. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you are at it, get to know your neighbors.

Alright, so, why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there certain rules or limits that guide the path of evolutionary change? Well, back in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that even then, scientists were barely scratching the surface of defining organic forms mathematically. Fast forward to today, and we're using math to understand mollusks' skeleton growth over time through both individual development and across generations. Our research is all about blending mathematical modeling with experiments to figure out how growth and size changes happen. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to spot key measurements and entered them into a software called CerioShell. By creating hypothetical shell shapes, we're exploring the limits of possible changes in Prunum. And we're combining this with experiments and descriptions to better grasp the big picture of evolution in this group.

Imagine a shell as a tube that wraps around a central axis called the columella, spinning in 360-degree loops called whorls. The speed at which these whorls grow varies, and a continuous line separates each one, known as a suture. The biggest whorl is usually the last one, called the body whorl, and the rest are part of the spire. The shell's tip is called the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal exits through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, or abapertural. The most common way to view a shell is apertural, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, start by looking at the shell from the apical view, find the first suture, and draw a line through it. Count whorls from there, estimating to a quarter of a whorl as needed.

A shell can be thought of as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. You can trace this path using the center of each whorl's aperture and the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture. This trajectory can be shown both graphically and mathematically. Once you have a mathematical formula, you can tweak parameters to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

So, another decade has rolled by, and it seems life in Indonesia, at least when it comes to neonatal and infant mortality, has been rather stagnant. The nation's progress in meeting the Millennium Development Goals is noteworthy, with marked improvements in water and sanitation. However, the pace of progress in reducing child and maternal health issues is far from where it needs to be by 2015. Let's delve into the reasons behind these shortcomings and why we should focus on strengthening the overall health system rather than just tweaking specific programs.

A positive sign is that 72% of births now see a skilled health worker, but this includes traditional workers like midwives who can't handle complications. This improvement is misleading, as there's still much work to be done. Additionally, the treatment of diarrheal cases in children under five has decreased, and postnatal care is an area of concern with low rates nationwide.

Cesarian-section rates are still dismally low at 4%, with urban areas at 7% and rural areas at just 2%, indicating a severe equity gap in healthcare access. This disparity is further exacerbated by a 27% gap in service utilization between the richest and poorest quintiles, suggesting that the poor struggle to access healthcare services likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care, the most crucial question is how to best address the lack of service. Should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system? Programmatic approaches are appealing due to their targeted, manageable nature and faster results. However, investing heavily in one area may starve other sectors of funding and resources, leading to a duplication of uncoordinated services and an increase in administrative burdens.

Victorian literature is renowned for its meticulous attention to detail and its focus on the aristocracy of the era. However, two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels diverge from the norm by incorporating elements of mystery and the bizarre, which serve to enrich the characters and provide deeper insights into their motivations and emotions. Both works employ dream sequences or dreamlike states to convey this sense of mystery, though the specifics vary in each case.

In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often unveil Oliver's inner turmoil, revealing what troubles him and his awareness of the true nature of his surroundings. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he relives the event vividly, as if in a dream, while struggling to find help. This passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events and his dire physical condition, as reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself leaves Oliver overwhelmed, his senses numbed as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" that bears him away; he experiences his despair anew, removed from the initial shock of pain, as the pain becomes constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. The question arises as to whose will brought about his misfortune, as it certainly wasn't his own. This shooting underscores Oliver's limited control over his circumstances, even as his life is in danger. Furthermore, it suggests a growing sense of defeat, as if Fagin has begun to break him, compelling him to accept this despair and influencing his ability to react. It can be assumed that if Oliver were not resigned to this despair, he would have made at least a minimal effort to save himself.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

Back in the day, I worked as a tutor for an after-school program, helping elementary kids with their homework. While I excelled in English and reading, I was recruited to assist a kid named Adrian, who was having a rough time with reading. Initially, it seemed like he had peculiar reading problems, but it turned out his issue was that he could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well. I finally realized this when his mom walked in, speaking only Spanish. With my fledgling Spanish skills, we managed to communicate. That day, I understood Adrian's struggle, and I hope he's doing better now. I share this story to highlight the language barrier in schools, particularly in California. It's not always as evident as we think, and even kids who speak perfect English can struggle with reading due to alphabet and pronunciation issues. The solution isn't simple; it requires a combination of approaches, like dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, and ESL classes. For Adrian, tutoring in English reading and pronunciation was effective, but for kids who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. The key is combining all these methods to address the language barrier effectively.

From childhood, many of us are taught that something larger than ourselves exists, something we can't comprehend. Some of us learn about it through Sunday school or religious institutions, while others look within themselves or reject it altogether, embracing our own egocentric universe. Each of us defines our spirituality through our unique perspectives, searching for light in the darkness to guide us. When my father passed away, he was, in many ways, already gone. I chose not to witness his departure, preferring to remember him through his life rather than his death. I couldn't let the knowledge of his passing make it more real for both of us, so I curled up in a ball in my bed, waiting for the news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel," as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, is essentially an "old-new" oxymoron. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and celebrated, accused of lacking depth, and praised for its 'terrible sublime' quality (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged ideas from both "ancient" and "modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary approach. Walpole combined old theatrical elements and modern mimicry of nature in his 'modern' novels, presenting what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre often incorporates throwbacks to medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to modern societal and literary advancements. The blend of the more theatrical "Gothic" style and the new novel format, which allowed readers a more personal view of character psychology, kept Gothic relevant for a long time, making it both obsolete and new to readers far removed from the original time.

One of the key themes in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, or the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of that ideal in their contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the genre's evolution towards Romanticism, and used to try and improve the present. Walpole, when he wrote The Castle of Otranto, was living in a politically tumultuous era and grappling with the possibility of a troubled future. Immersed in politics and unfair accusations, he may have begun to believe, if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" of people in the Gothic era had been lost in the individuals making up the 'present' society. This sentiment is evident in several characters, one being Frederic. The reader learns about Frederic before meeting him, and he embodies many chivalric traits: he is a prince, has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he leaves, and is currently thought to be killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, bringing into play the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the chain of events that moves goods from an initial customer order through to the stage of raw materials, production, distribution, and final delivery to the customer. The term "supply chain management" was coined in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant, who described it as the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to meet customers' needs efficiently. This process revolves around six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these elements to ensure optimal customer service.

The first crucial step in the supply chain is production. Production is foundational to the entire process. Managers must understand what customers want, which can be gauged by studying the market. The market's demands influence what products should be produced and in what quantities. Once the market study is complete, managers determine where and which plant would be best for production, considering volume and quality requirements. The next step is scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Each detail in production is vital, and any oversight can result in significant time and money losses. For instance, I previously worked at Wal-Mart and Target, where every aspect of the business had a designated process, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. These outlined processes ensure smooth operations and clarity in expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply, which involves strategic decisions to shape the core capabilities of a facility and form partnerships for outsourcing. A company may have multiple divisions for producing a single product, each with unique equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division best fits the product's processes. Outsourcing can also be a strategy to create velocity, which is the ability to offer high-quality and flexible services while minimizing costs.

The sign reads: "Hitler lives on in Burma." Ellen Page, the actor from the movie Juno, stands alone on a city street with a cardboard sign held high, the chilling message written in Sharpie. Burma, or Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a brutal military junta that seized control in 1962 following a coup d'état. In 2007, a series of public protests known as "The Saffron Revolution" erupted, sparked by monks. Initially, the government tolerated these peaceful gatherings, but the violence soon escalated as the military attacked monasteries nation-wide. Foreign journalists were arrested, and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed during a protest on September 27th, 2007. The official death toll stands at 13, but a defected colonel claims many more were killed, numbering potentially in the thousands.

This isn't a new trend. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control over their citizens. Early Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors were considered gods, and even our current president, George W. Bush, allegedly holds weekly meetings with Ted Haggard of Stupid People Worldwide, a branch of the Republican Party.

Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protest, where intellectuals, workers, and students gathered to challenge the government's authoritarian rule, with death tolls ranging from 200 to 3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s involved Hutu militias and the government systematically killing Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's "Third Reich" was a period of systematic persecution and murder of individuals of Jewish background across multiple countries.

Duke Ellington's enduring impact on jazz is greatly due to his longevity and the creative prowess he brought to his orchestra. Often seen as a subtle pianist in many of his compositions, Ellington excelled in composing rich and complex pieces that highlighted each band member's unique abilities. He established a framework where soloists could freely improvise, writing tightly orchestrated sections that showcased each player's style. This not only emphasized the tone of the orchestra but also created a unique and coherent sound for every piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players' sounds, as well as how they blended together into a cohesive ensemble, resulted in some of jazz's most innovative and brilliant works. The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's use of voice as a jazz instrument, exemplified in Creole Love Call, where he utilized the voice to add texture and color without lyrics. This piece is notable for its six choruses, each featuring different instrumental sections and soloists, demonstrating Ellington's ability to complement his soloists' styles. In Hot and Bothered and It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington continued to excel at tight orchestration and tone color, using unique combinations of vocal and instrumental elements to create rich, complementary sounds.

She had always felt this gnawing emptiness, a longing that couldn't be satisfied. It began when she was 14, just starting to navigate teenage life, and it persisted at 17. She had come to realize she desired a certain someone rather than some material possession, but no boy had caught her interest. Several had tried to woo her, with varying degrees of clumsiness, but none sparked the spark she craved. She often pondered this peculiar situation, wondering what could be the cause. Years of introspection offered theories, but nothing concrete enough to give her any clarity. So, she continued living her life, perpetually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually serene and peaceful. Her parents were calm and harmonious, rarely arguing with each other or her. The only disputes were over her asserting her independence and unique personality. They were fond of her for her lively spirit, which complemented their laid-back nature, making her well-liked and nice.

Today, however, was not a typical peaceful day. As she moved from room to room, searching for inspiration, a sudden shriek from the kitchen pierced the air. She rushed in to find her mother lying on the floor, in obvious pain. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she cried out in panic. Her mother managed to whisper, "Ouch...sweetie...I...need you to take me to the hospital." Her daughter quickly sprang into action, helped her mother into the car, and drove them to the nearest hospital.

The hospital was filled with the familiar scent of disinfectant and the underlying aroma of sickness. She wasn't focused on that, though; her mind was consumed with worrying about her mother. She rushed her mother to the nearest doctor, who immediately set to work. Her daughter was left to wait, her heart pounding with anxiety.

Her mother had fallen from a ladder while trying to reach a high cabinet. The doctor's assessment was clear: her mother needed critical care.

This research aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed), is linked to reduced chances of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is a tweaked version of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, while also lowering intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Previous research found an inverse relationship between following the Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular mortality (CVD), and showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in overweight individuals. However, these studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Every six years from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed score from self-reported food frequency questionnaires (FFQs). More than 95% of nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Cases without available records were considered "probable" and included, with around 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, with leisure-time physical activity assessed starting in 1986.

To minimize random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated. Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could confuse results) by considering age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between the aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, there were 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined). Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Well, you know what happened in '07, it was a complete financial meltdown. Jobless rates soared, the housing market tanked, and many big shots in business were left in the dust. We've been feeling the effects ever since. I reckon we should ask ourselves, how did it all go south, and how can we avoid it happening again? Now, the crisis was cooked up by politicians who were pushing banks to give out sub-prime loans, even though the financial system wasn't ready. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were also under pressure to back these mortgages and then resell them as CDOs and CDSs. When people started defaulting on these loans, the banks were left high and dry, and it all cascaded into a full-blown economic disaster.

The seeds of this mess were sown back in '99 during the Clinton era. The President was eyeing a second term, and he wanted to boost his popularity. So, he relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime fiasco just seven years later. Steven Holmes, writing for the New York Times, warned back then, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest mortgage underwriter, was facing increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgages for low and moderate-income people and from stockholders to keep growing profits.” Holmes was right on the mark: ill-advised lending would indeed bring about the economic meltdown.

A lot of things combined to send the economy into a spin. Mortgages were getting more complicated, with adjustable rates, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs becoming common. This only made the housing market more interconnected with the rest of the economy, leaving people and financial markets vulnerable to any little price changes.

And then, the housing bubble burst. Banks that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were left with nothing but sour faces. The top five U.S. investment banks reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007—that's about 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch got sold off cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become commercial banks, all under intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were in $5 trillion worth of mortgage debt and were put under government control in September 2008. It was a mess, and it all started with some bad political decisions.

So here we are, exposition time. That's the part where you spread your writer's wings and either captivate or bore your readers. Dr. Merlin, she's known to shout at her monitor when caught in the throes of Too Much Information, and not in the fun kind of way either.

We all know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still finds herself in the muck of long-winded text where nothing much happens, or worse, too much. Exposition is that little devil on your shoulder telling you to get the history out of the way to get to the good stuff, not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder who wants you to dump every detail of your characters' pasts onto your audience.

Exposition means just telling the audience what happened, typically in straightforward prose. In movies, it's when one character pours out a bunch of info to another, like the Ancient Mariner. In fiction, the author does the pouring.

Consider this: you're reading along and are told the heroine met her love at such a place and time, they were married in a grand fashion, and he was murdered in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to stretch over two pages, with only a handful of lines of dialogue. You'd expect a bit more than just the bare facts—some insight into how he loved her, how she changed because of him. You'd mourn his death with her, and thus, become more connected to her character.

In short, you'd expect some meat on the simple bone of the story: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, presses on*) It's tempting to rush past certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he was once in the Air Force, now runs a gas station at night, has been married twice, no kids, loves fishing on weekends, and dreams of owning the station someday, just had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

But you gotta slow down and provide those details. Show us who he is, not just tell us.

I caught two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio, today (August 13, 2011). The first was a "live" segment on NBC 4. The lead story was about a guy named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who stabbed his wife – they didn't mention her name. His mug shot was shown, and he had an eerie look about him. They only spent about two minutes on this story, which seemed appropriate given it was still developing.

The second story was about the shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old, in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, and there were no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was investigating. This story felt short, and I suspect that might be due to the fact that it involved a "black" man or a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that minorities are often overlooked when they're victims of crimes. If it were a "white" child or adult, the media would go crazy, but for a minority, it's lucky if it's even mentioned.

Next up, they discussed a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where the incident might have occurred, and it was determined to be a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a five-thousand-dollar reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.

Then, they talked about rain and thunderstorms expected for Saturday afternoon. They mentioned the temperatures would stay in the mid to low eighties over the weekend. The story was a bit short, but it was used as a teaser to keep us tuned in.

They also ran a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned black man in a hoodie sweatshirt, about six feet tall and 150 pounds. They devoted an unusual amount of time talking about his race and how dark he was, which felt excessive.

Finally, they mentioned a convicted drug kingpin named Rene Rodriguez. He was a Hispanic man from Texas, convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio. Instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure why they did that, perhaps to make it sound harsher. They also mentioned his Hispanic background, which I don't think was really relevant to the story.

There is an unbreakable bond between brothers, a connection that is as complex as it is profound. This bond carries with it a range of emotions - love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers, more than anyone else, understand each other deeply. They can see themselves reflected in their brother's eyes, seeing not how others perceive them, but their true selves. It's in moments of crisis that this bond truly shines, revealing the good and the bad. When these feelings surface, they come with a hefty price tag. Understanding these emotions, and their consequences, is part of appreciating the weight of this fraternal connection. When a brother looks at you, they see not just you, but your essence. Their actions and the outcomes of those actions unveil their true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," this theme is explored through the journey of two brothers. Through their interactions and the narrator's perspective, the intense emotions that accompany this bond are vividly depicted. The protagonist's feelings are dominated by one emotion: pride. From their first adventure together to their final, tragic outing, the protagonist feels resentment towards his younger brother, Doodle. He dreams of teaching Doodle all the skills he knows, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing Old Woman Swamp vines. He wants a brother to race with to Horsehead Landing and to perch with in the great pine tree. These dreams are shattered when Doodle's weak heart condition is revealed. The protagonist is filled with anger, even considering suffocating Doodle with a pillow. Yet, his heart softens when Doodle smiles at him. This moment of weakness in his conviction shows the love he has, albeit hidden, for his brother.

The human brain is a complex, innovative information processor. As technology evolved from primitive to contemporary times, so did the analogies used to describe the brain. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and most recently, a computer. As you delve into the brain, remember that these metaphors are limited in their usefulness and can lead to misconceptions. Information processing begins with input from the senses, converting physical sensations such as touch, heat, sound, or light into electrochemical signals. The sensory data is continually transformed by the brain's algorithms, both through bottom-up and top-down processes. For instance, when you see a black box against a white background, bottom-up processing helps determine the object's simple properties like color, orientation, and edges. Top-down processing speeds up recognition by using decisions made from previous steps. This could help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the background. Once data is processed, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes should access it. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. However, you might pick out your name in a noisy room. Numerous processing stages exist, with results modulated by attention repeatedly. To process information, the brain must first store it. Various memory types include sensory, working, and long-term memory. Information is encoded uniquely for each sensory stimulus type, such as structurally for printed words, phonemically for sounds, or semantically for meanings. Once stored, information must be maintained, and studies suggest working memory uses electrical signals looping through neurons for a short period. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in specific protein structures. Several models describe how knowledge is organized in the brain, including those based on human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented as nodes linked by their relatedness. For example, "chair" might be linked to "table," which could be linked to "wooden," and so forth.

Aldous Huxley takes a critical stance against the impending threat of both technology and the capitalist system that supports it, as depicted in his dystopian novel Brave New World. The people in this society prioritize community over individuality and are conditioned from birth to pursue immediate gratification. The citizens are essentially pawns in a grand game, controlled by the World Controller who dictates their ideology. Analyzing the novel through the lens of Marxist criticism, we find that Huxley's reservations about the development of these systems are evident. Terms like homogenization and reification reinforce the idea that the novel is a commentary on the flaws in the emerging economy during Huxley's time.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness, a Marxist thesis. Essentially, common citizens are prevented from understanding their true economic relations to other classes, as they are primarily focused on their own interests. This is a result of ideological control over the proletariat and the laboring classes, evident in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The various social classes, such as Delta and Gamma, lack any real will of their own, as their drive to consume and indulge is strengthened through hypnopædia. This manipulation is carried out by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that one social class is dominated by another, is clearly present here. The lower classes are completely unaware of this manipulation, essentially 'buying into an ideology that supports the structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). Even the upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, typically accept their place, with few exceptions like Bernard. The interactions between the social classes also indicate the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals are shallow and lack depth. Characters, even the major ones, are not well-defined, suggesting that technology and capitalism together may deprive people of their free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent, with interactions kept superficial. Males often comment on women's physical attributes, while females discuss their encounters. This superficiality indicates the socioeconomic effect of capitalism. The absolute obedience of each societal class to their role in the community reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority so long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to their peers.

I've been a student at University Park for nearly two and a half years, which is four and a half semesters. Getting around campus can be a real challenge. During my freshman year, I was stuck in an East Halls dorm, the farthest from the center of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in places like Willard building, which is near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes, especially on days when the weather was bad. I talked to an older alum who told me that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by vast empty fields. Now, those spaces are filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and the new health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As the campus continues to grow, navigating from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What's the best solution to this mobility problem? The answer is bicycles. But having a bike doesn't solve all problems. Students need to ride them regularly, and the campus needs to be designed with cyclists in mind.

Just the other day, I was chatting with a friend who recently started cycling again after taking a break. He said, "Bikes are fantastic! For a few years, they weren't the coolest thing to ride, but they're the only way to commute around." Cycling is not only good for your body but also the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical exertion can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from the center as some dorms are. The best decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have a class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding my bike can cut that time down to just 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. However, Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas from my house, and it's not always an easy road to navigate, whether by bike or on foot. There are certainly benefits to walking, but I barely have time for that. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day. That's more than two and a half hours each week. Add to that the time I'd spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and so on. That's more time than I can spare.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli.
