The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do‭? ‬Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change‭? ‬Although in‭ ‬1917‭ ‬D’Arcy Thompson stated that‭ “‬Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms‭” ‬the same can be said today. More recently,‭ ‬mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny‭ (‬e.g.,‭ ‬Raup and Stanley,‭ ‬1981‭)‬. Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum,‭ ‬in combination with experimental studies,‭ ‬can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell‭ (‬Stone,‭ ‬1995‭)‬. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through‭ ‬360‭ ‬degrees of space.  These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls,‭ ‬which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis.  This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary,‭ ‬and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture.  In most shells,‭ ‬the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl‭ (‬body whorl‭)‬.  ‭ ‬The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical,‭ ‬basal,‭ ‬apertural and abapertural views. ‭(‬The‭ "‬usual‭" ‬orientation of a shell is an apertural view,‭ ‬with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.‭)‬

A method for counting whorls is seen below.  First,‭ ‬the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins.  A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts.  Whorls are counted from this line,‭ ‬and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes‭ (‬i.e. builds‭) ‬its shell.  It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented.  Once a mathematical formulation is made,‭ ‬it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia remained rather static for the last ten years.  While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015.  The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  That being said, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage).  In other words,  the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done.  In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.
	Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%.  The c-section rates additionally point to another concerning issue.  While the rate of c-section is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural.  This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country.  Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas.  Another issue of access concerns vertical equity.  There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.
	In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service.  Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child.  There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive.  Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results.  There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example).  In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs.  This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In my quest to become a social worker, I aim to focus on the Division of Family and Children Services. My goal is to support children who have been abused or neglected and offer assistance to troubled families. The values I bring to this field are service, respect, an ethical nature, and a commitment to improving relationships and my own professional competence. These values are not just beneficial to the social work field; they are integral to my personal being.

I've always had a strong desire to help others, but I was uncertain about the career path I wanted to take. Throughout high school and college, I observed many individuals dodging their problems and employing subpar coping mechanisms. Witnessing these situations led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Even after graduation from Piedmont College in 2009, I was still uncertain about my career. During a summer break, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. He was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I found out he had called the police to his parents' residence. I drove over to help and privately explained my concerns to the police. They requested that I speak with the parents, as there was nothing the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and blamed their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outsiders. This experience made me consider a career in social work to help children with "simple" family disputes.

Another crucial value for social work is social justice. While society claims to value each individual, the concept of “the individual” is often more aligned with traditional norms than actual uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and refuse to limit myself to be like others. Throughout my schooling, I protested against social injustice: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that reflected my personality, piercing my ears beyond the norm, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination. I stand for social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

So, this paper dives into the Biological and Sociocultural models concerning the disorder insomnia. The biological model zooms in on genetic info passed down, as well as the medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models, on the other hand, explore environmental relationships and their implications on race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review examines insomnia through these models, breaking down each piece of research related to them and explaining it better. We’ll also critique the research findings and point out their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders linked to another mental disorder, or sleep disorders due to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders linked to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other sleep disorders can stem from medical complications or substance use. Dyssomnias, such as Primary Insomnia and Primary Hypersomnia, each have their specific characteristics. Primary Insomnia, for instance, is a struggle with adequate or maintained sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia is difficulty staying awake for at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. Meanwhile, Parasomnias, like Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, and Sleepwalking Disorder, are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder deal with sleep difficulties caused by Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). Our review focuses mainly on insomnia and primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, inherited factors, and the physiological aspects of these disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus, containing orexin, are crucial for regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice found specific GABAB receptors on orexin neurons that regulate sleep and wake states. Activating the GABAA receptor, which is inhibited by baclofen, can increase sleep time. This suggests that animal models like mice can be generalized to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for GABAB receptors in humans. If these receptors are impaired, adequate sleep without medication could be affected. The sociocultural implication is that inherited phenotypes could naturally regulate sleep, and alterations in these receptors could disturb sleep, negatively impacting daily life, including school, career, and monotonous tasks.

This article takes a look at three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Firstly, it provides a brief definition of the condition, describing it as a problem with the efficiency and effectiveness of how the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In simpler terms, it’s a disorder where the brain struggles to properly process sounds we hear, even though the ears are functioning normally. People with CAPD can hear just fine, but the part of the brain responsible for separating words and filtering out background noise doesn't work as it should.

The origins of CAPD can be traced back to the mid-1950s, initially referred to as “auditory imperception”. Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started developing tests for children with communication disorders in 1954. Kimura then introduced dichotic testing in 1961, which helped understand how the brain processes auditory information. A national conference in 1977 further sparked research on CAPD.

The disorder can manifest in various ways. A person with CAPD might have trouble pinpointing where sounds are coming from, distinguishing between different sounds, recognizing patterns, or detecting changes in speech. They may also struggle with sounds being blocked by subsequent ones, or have difficulty interpreting sounds to act upon them. Additionally, they might have trouble understanding the sequence of sounds presented to them.

Diagnosing CAPD involves a systematic observation of a patient’s listening behavior and performance on tests of auditory function. This can be done by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, or others using various measures. There’s no single, consistent tool for diagnosis, and the cause of CAPD is unknown. Tests often present multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask the patient to differentiate items like words or numbers. More advanced tests record acoustic signals in the ear and measure responses to them.

Lastly, the article concludes with ways a teacher in a mainstream classroom can assist a student with CAPD.

So, Twelfth Night seems to suggest that while disguise can be handy for pulling off long deceits, at some point, you gotta drop it and return to your true self, or else you might lose yourself forever. The tricky part? When you reveal your true colors, you might find yourself all alone. Some folks won't mind being deceived, but others might take it hard. Like, really hard. At the end of the day, you gotta choose between staying true to yourself or keeping your relationships intact. Now, gender role reversal and deception is a whole different ball game. Why would someone feel the need to ditch their own identity and pretend to be someone else? In Viola's case, it's all about self-preservation. “I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249) New in town and scared, Viola pretends to be a man to stay safe. Her plan works, but it cuts her off from the women in her life, leaving her isolated. To make things worse, she's so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) Plus, she's dealing with Orsino's unrequited feelings: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261) Now, this might all seem progressive, but to us modern folk, it might be seen as a way to surface hidden emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. It's like Shakespeare is saying, hey, maybe they've got feelings they're not aware of yet. Take Olivia, for instance. Is she into Cesario because he's a man or does she secretly fancy women? Probably not, since Olivia seems more like a product of her time, judging people only by their looks. Case in point, she easily switches her affections from Cesario to Sebastian, treating Cesario/Viola as family instead. “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

So let's delve into the intricacies of German colonial rule. Now, I'm not saying it was all one thing. We're talking about an empire here, and empires are complex beasts. The German colonial empire was a patchwork of policies and governance, as varied as it was vast. But when it comes to education, it was a mixed bag too. In colonies like German East Africa (now Tanzania), the Brits found a literate and educated population. And in Kamerun and other colonies, the Germans got some kudos for their educational efforts. But South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) was a different story. Unlike East Africa, where the government took the reins in educating the locals, in South West Africa, it was largely left to missionary societies with meager government support. Meanwhile, the government invested heavily in European education. This had lingering effects long after German rule ended, with a vast majority of the population remaining uneducated. Social, political, and economic factors were the drivers behind this disparity. This is what I want to explore further, looking at new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There's a ton of literature out there on education in the German colonial empire. Most of it's in German and came out in the early 20th century, either during or soon after the colonial period. Early works were all about describing the educational systems in each colony. Later works in English gave us more detailed comparisons and analyses. These studies highlighted the significant differences between the educational systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa is a standout here. Cohen compares the two colonies and discusses the factors behind their educational differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa played a big role in shaping its educational system.

South West Africa was moderately temperate, but much of it was arid desert. This attracted a European population—nearly 15,000 whites by 1913. In comparison, East Africa had only 5,336 settlers.

The classification of popular music has evolved significantly over the past 100 years, leading us to a point where listing all the genres and sub-genres can be quite challenging. Genres like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, for example, have birthed numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, making it even harder to keep track. One such genre that stands out for its diversity and expressiveness is Heavy Metal rock, which has developed into a highly versatile genre over the past 40 years. It’s expressive because it covers a wide range of emotions, predominantly leaning towards the darker side. Its diversity is evident in the early realization that it offered ample flexibility for experimentation, leading to the creation of various sub-genres and sub-sub-genres that continue to flourish today.

We’ve reached a point where the Heavy Metal movement has spawned so many unique groups that it's almost impossible to define what Heavy Metal is. It has absorbed themes from other genres, but it has a distinct origin. To understand the metal music of today, one must first grasp what the metal movement is and why it’s considered a movement rather than just a genre.

Heavy Metal is fundamentally a dark movement. It’s often described as a “music of more”—more bass, more volume, more intensity, more theatricality. Musicians in metal bands are highly skilled, which is evident in their music. It’s also a movement deeply influenced by drug culture. The mid-70s saw a psychedelic drug boom that led to the creation of crazier, otherworldly music, often using drugs as an excuse for its unique sound. The genre possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which was a new trend at the time, as much of popular music earlier didn’t delve into the darker emotions. Later generations of metal musicians have also drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral qualities of the Romantic Era. Lyrics like the following showcase the darker side of the movement:

These lyrics from Helter Skelter exhibit the darker side of the Beatles. The song is seen as one of the first Heavy Metal songs, responding to a Rolling Stone song that was also on the heavier, darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove their ability to be as heavy as the Stones, leading to the inclusion of Helter Skelter on their White Album.

So a few decades before the Surrealists started painting their dreamlike masterpieces, there was Henri Rousseau, a man who was figuratively and literally crafting his own dreams. The Dream, a painting from 1910, isn't just a depiction of a woman in awe of a dream landscape; it's a reflection of Rousseau's own aspirations as an artist. From the start, he dreamt of recognition, acceptance, and praise, but faced a tough internal struggle. Should he conform to existing styles to be accepted or stay true to his unique voice? The Dream captures this lifelong battle: his desire to be part of the art world versus his wish to carve his own path.

To understand The Dream, we need to know a bit about Rousseau's life. Born in Laval, France, on May 21, 1844, he was a tinsmith's son who never received formal art training. He worked as a gabelou until he was forty, earning the nickname "douanier" despite not being a customs inspector. After losing his first wife and many of their children, he turned to painting for solace. Unlike his peers, Rousseau was a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of the common people.

Rousseau's quest for acceptance is understandable given his circumstances. Uneducated and starting late, he was painting amidst more famous artists, and his recognition came around the same time as Matisse's rise. Jan Gordon, in Modern French Painters, notes that while they were rivals, they had different motivations. Matisse wanted to avoid clichés, while Rousseau wanted to create something so conventional he’d be accepted.

So many great minds have posited a deep bond between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there's a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats wrote in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty— / That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. Yet, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being formally taught. Both are efforts to describe, rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty often aim to explain why something is beautiful or moral, rather than setting rules for good art or moral behavior. For instance, discussing da Vinci's Mona Lisa may focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these don't fully capture why it's good art. When asked about a favorite piece, people often say, "There's just something about it," followed by a more complex explanation. I believe that both art and morals can't be fully reduced to their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor put it, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... You tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Ethics shares this property. As Wittgenstein said, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that this elusive "something," this je ne sais quoi, is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and it's this transcendental nature that connects them. I believe morality and art are so closely related because we experience them most powerfully at a noumenal level, as Kant would say. They affect us at a level we can feel but can't fully explain. This link is especially strong with literature. As McKean notes, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Germany, as it stands today, is recognized as a potent force, a united nation with a rich culture that stretches from the alpine shadows of Munich to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This culture is tangible in cities like Cologne, in the heart of Germany, and in Dresden, a Saxon city nestled along the Elbe. Given this diverse cultural tapestry, it's not surprising that Germany, as we know it, has its roots in various sources and tribes.

The land of the Germans, known as Germania, has a contentious origin story. Some scholars believe the name came from the Germanic tribe called Tungrians, as documented by Tacitus in 98 AD, while others suggest it might come from the Old Irish word meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans were loud or noisy. Regardless, the Romans, who first used the term "Germanus" to distinguish conquered Gauls from unconquered Germanic tribes, would have been surprised to see the Germanic tribes living on the borders of their empire. Initially, the Romans interacted with the Germanic tribes through trade and the occasional military campaign, but mostly returned to their sprawling empire. The Germanic tribes, however, remained, and their influence continued to shape the lands they inhabited.

Staring down, I blankly took in the sight before me. My mind was unemotionally processing the view, silently analyzing it with a practiced precision that refused to relate the object to any abstract understanding. Thoughts flitted in and out of my consciousness almost too quickly to notice. It was as if I was experiencing the scene rather than thinking about it.
Years ago, an artist I worked with recommended an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had always wanted to learn how to draw, and this book promised to teach even the basics of understanding a pencil and how the brain interprets lines. One technique it taught was to place a square frame around any picture to simplify a complex scene. Standing there, I couldn't mentally project that frame onto the bowl of fruit in front of me. I was too overwhelmed, too awed by the prospect of painting. If I had any pretensions to being artistic, this was my first canvas, my first story: "Work in Brown."
Fingertips resting on the brush handle, muscles tensing and relaxing as I moved my hand through space, I was about to capture a moment of creativity. Water circled, clear and calm, crystal clear and clean. Matter broke away and was swept away. My hand hit the handle again, muscles tightening more this time, a little more anxious. The brown package refused to budge. It was stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.
Mop in hand, feet spread apart, tie knotted tightly around my throat, I frowned at the offensive bundle of food waste left for the bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more quiet moments, then my hand reached for the wall, the end of the toilet paper. I wrapped it around my hand until it looked like an oven mitt. Standing up straight, I bent down, my hand slowly entering the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey.

Another tragic trend that's been making headlines lately is the alarming number of teenagers dying behind the wheel. Several factors are at play here, and it's a deadly combination. The National Institutes of Health point out that the teen brain isn't fully mature for driving yet, and this immaturity, combined with sheer inexperience, leads to more fatal crashes, vehicle rollovers, speeding tickets, and off-road incidents. Add to that the fact that teens often drive with friends, which is something anyone with a speck of wisdom knows they do frequently. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found that the number of traffic accidents increases with the age of the passengers in the car.

To tackle this issue, some states have introduced temporary provisional licenses that restrict teens to drive only during certain hours and ban other minors as passengers. However, these measures are just temporary fixes. The real problem is that, as a group, young drivers just aren't ready to handle the risks and responsibilities of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a full driver's license. He's found that teens under 19 or 20 often crave excitement and take risks for the thrill of it, and it makes sense to delay driving until these tendencies mellow out. If we keep issuing driver's licenses to young teens, we're looking at more deadly crashes and a potential surge in teen deaths in just a few years. By 2010, the Baby Boomers' children will be eligible to drive, adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads.

Addressing this issue through legislation could be relatively simple. Schools could start teaching future drivers, but no one under 18 could actually drive a car. Provisional permits could still be issued, and teens would need to complete a certain number of hours of driving practice with an adult, similar to the requirements in most states. The specific number could be based on the current standards (6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult in California, for example). As the statistics show, teen driving fatalities are a concern across all states, making a uniform national policy a reasonable and effective solution.

This proposed legislation isn't a groundbreaking idea, but it could make a significant difference in the safety of our young drivers.

So I decided to take a gander at the Library of Congress's collection of Edison's old films, specifically the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films were basically all about creative editing to create illusions. My film study focused on describing the poetic elements of most trick films and examining the unique characteristics of a few of the later ones. The trick films of the time were pretty much confined to a set, framed within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, long and medium shots, and sticking to the one shot, one film rule.

But some of these films at the beginning of the twentieth century were bold enough to break these rules by introducing aspects like multiple shots. One thing that stood out in these trick films was their filming style. They were shot in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera didn't move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects, drawing from the theatre and vaudeville tradition. Figures in trick films generally only moved side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), the actors entered from the right and moved back and forth along the horizontal axis, without the camera following them.

The frontal proscenium setup also meant that shots were typically long shots or, less often, medium shots. Close-ups were never used in any of the Edison trick films. This again was borrowed from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. Since actors didn't move towards the camera, close-ups were non-existent.

Most of these early trick films followed the pattern of one conceptual shot equaling a film. This usually kept the films short, about a minute or less, and limited their dramatic or narrative use. They mainly focused on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing, and switching acts, with little story. However, what appeared to be one conceptual shot to the viewer actually wasn't necessarily one physical shot. A single "shot" could be made up of several joined together to create illusions like apparition or disappearing. Take The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) as an example. A closer look reveals that the physical shot with Mary's "head" starts, even though the film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate supporter of the Republican cause. Despite being primarily a farmer, his time in politics and his commitment to his profession instilled in him a deep dedication to personal liberty and the principles of government. His devotion to an agrarian lifestyle shaped nearly all of his views on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique opportunity to establish a perfect system because no native traditions hindered its founding, allowing for a government of self-governance. He held firm beliefs in the interdependence of natural rights and the need for them to be beyond government control. He argued that those with physical strength and cunning took advantage in a state of nature, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must account for human nature’s inherent good and evil. He was rigid in his dualistic morality, stating, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He considered principles that protected private property, improved agriculture, and discouraged capitalism as good, and believed a government founded on these principles would function fairly despite its corruptible administration.

Taylor, like many of his contemporaries, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He favored a minimal Federal government, only granting it powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He acknowledged that an expansive Federal government could become tyrannical due to its cost, but he also cautioned that a simple, literal interpretation could lead to corruption without considering the founders' intent. The Declaration of Independence, he believed, was the true charter of the United States, as it explicitly described the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at Figure 17, we noticed a significant drop in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project. This was quite disheartening, and it's tough to pinpoint the exact cause. With winter setting in at the New England campus, commuting by bicycle or on foot naturally declined. December also marks the end of the fall semester, a time when everyone is busy with schoolwork and grading. Filling out the commuter log might have gotten lost in the shuffle. Plus, December brings the holiday season, often resulting in a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January for the spring semester, which might have contributed to the low log submissions for that month. However, February's low submissions remain unexplained. The project might just have experienced an initial burst of energy that naturally faded. To boost engagement, we organized the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did indeed increase log submissions. This highlights the challenge of maintaining project momentum during natural engagement dips and holiday/semester breaks. Another hurdle for this project, or any similar initiative, is the deeply ingrained culture of driving personal cars for commuting. To encourage alternative commuting, we offered gift certificates to local businesses like restaurants, coffee shops, a bookstore, and even national chains. It would have been interesting to see the impact of larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars. If we had gradually increased the prize value over time, it might have boosted participation and engagement. The gift cards were effective at the start, but announcing larger prizes in December and January could have sustained and possibly even increased participation.

Another financial tool to consider is an ETF, or exchange-traded fund. Unlike index funds, ETFs offer more flexibility and trade like individual stocks on an exchange. They bring the diversification of an index fund and the perks of owning a single stock, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share. The advantages are clear, but so are some drawbacks. Like stocks, ETFs charge commissions on trades, and while their expense ratios are lower than mutual funds, they can still add up.

A savvy investor should assess whether the benefits of owning an ETF, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent. For this effort, let's examine the ETF IHF and compare it to its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's total assets. The top 10 holdings are listed below along with their respective percentages.

To gauge how well these top 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, let's calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, normalized to 100%. The results of these calculations are shown in the chart below.

The chart shows that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings yields a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase. Additionally, the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than that of the ETF as a whole. Initially, it seems a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower Beta. However, the statistical significance of these portfolios may not be different.

To determine if the portfolios are statistically different, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

Another one of Edgar Allan Poe's notable works is "Dream-Land," which he himself considered one of his better poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which, according to Mabbott, traces back to Virgil's writings. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. While it is certain that Virgil did use the term, there is a more contemporary source to which credit may also be given. Poe had a keen interest in German authors, especially the works of Goethe.

This is significant because it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," discusses the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, concluding that Poe was likely influenced by Goethe's work.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated writer, particularly known for his poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts—the first in 1808 and the second in the year of his death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust, there is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." This poem tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet as a gift. After her death, the king becomes consumed with drinking and grief, ultimately deciding to end his life. He gives away all his possessions to his children, except for the goblet, which he throws into the sea before deleting himself from the cliff. The descriptions of the King of Thule and the speaker in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, suggesting a dark reflection of Poe's own experiences and struggles with substance abuse.

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works. He uses the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but he also employs the term "Thule" as bookends for "Dream-Land." "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule, which is dark, lonely, and haunted by the memory of dead friends. The lack of color in the world mirrors the gloom of the King of Thule's situation after the loss of his wife. The entire poem is as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a significant author whose work Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his admiration for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe expressed that, aside from their connection, he would have been exposed to Goethe's work through numerous reproductions of his original publications.

In the case of Jennifer Palmer suing D&D Markets, California law may allow her to seek punitive damages if she can prove the store manager, Paul Martin, acted with malicious intent. Palmer needs to show that Martin was aware of the potential harm from the applesauce spill and deliberately disregarded it. Martin was informed about the spill twice, but he failed to have it cleaned for a half-hour because he was eating dinner. This could be considered malicious if he knew the previous incidents involving slip-and-fall injuries and chose not to act. Palmer's claim that Martin's actions were despicable is weaker but still reasonable considering the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009.

CBC was the place where I first delved into the teachings of Islam, four years ago now. The heated debates sparked in class about whether or not Islam is inherently hostile were as relevant then as they are today, perhaps even more so. Since 9/11, I've witnessed the media's view of Islam shifting from outright hostility towards extremists to an almost extreme tolerance. I doubt that, back in 2001, an American presidential candidate with an obvious Muslim background like Barack Obama could have been a possibility.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography has always intrigued me, as it seems to present a stark contrast to the historical accounts I've read. According to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a martyr and a humble figure who, rather than forcibly converting others, saw people come to him seeking the truth in his teachings. This depiction, however, doesn't align with the historical narrative of Muhammad's rise to power. It's as if the biography is trying to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, portraying him as wise, gentle, and humble. Yet, history contradicts this, and I can't help but wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true historical context surrounding Muhammad's rise.

Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad that intrigue me. For instance, the story of Muhammad multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men bears a striking resemblance to Jesus' miracle of feeding the five thousand. This style of writing, I believe, is an attempt to portray Muhammad as a humble prophet who, through his actions and teachings, demonstrates the truth without needing to prove anything. This approach, however, diminishes the life and miracles of Jesus, making it seem like they are borrowing credit from his life.

The biography also includes numerous stories that aim to provide 'witnesses' to the conversion of people to Islam. However, many of these tales are told from a third-party perspective, such as the author hearing the story from someone who heard it from another person. I found this approach to be less convincing, as it often diminishes the stories' credibility by adding layers of uncertainty. It's as if the authors were trying to build a case for the truth of the stories, but the third-party nature of many of them makes it seem more like a string of hearsay.

What troubles me the most about this work is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, and wise figure. This portrayal contradicts historical accounts of Muhammad's rise to power and makes me question whether modern Muslims are aware of the historical context surrounding his life.

So, the teachings of Jesus, the beliefs he held during his lifetime, were quickly left behind as Christianity evolved after his passing. Looking at this from a broad perspective, it's clear that Christianity has drifted further and further from its origins over time. Today, we see a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditional people persist and may resist any new thinking, they might not be enough to influence the entire population. Among believers, a historical awareness will undoubtedly grow in future years. There will be a longing to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from what Jesus originally intended. It may take decades or even centuries, but the end result will be inevitable: a return to the religion's original form. A movement will emerge, growing in numbers, and will peel away layers of doctrine, one by one, like a clock winding backward. When this trend reaches the United States and Europe, it will influence many to worship as if they were living during Jesus' time, following only his ideas. The church, as an institution, will remain strong to guide this path. However, as the theological clock reverses, the extreme diversity within Christendom will reduce to greater uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions, we'll see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with such reversals. For example, Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, but the empire later became a Christian institution. Our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal coming in the future will play out in the realm of Christianity, undoing history and diversity in the process. A key part of what will enable this process is interpreting Jesus' words as metaphorical, rather than literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime?
       If we delve deep into history, we find that Judaism was the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the belief in a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at the core of the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not unified in spirit, dividing into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, and Zealots, along with a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" illustrates how, deep down, humans are inherently selfish and focused solely on their own prosperity. They strive to make their lives as comfortable and successful as possible, without considering the well-being of those less fortunate. This is evident in the owners and managers of the massive factories, who are solely driven by the desire to expand their enterprises, often at the expense of others. They disregard any collateral damage caused by their relentless pursuit of growth. Upton Sinclair vividly portrays this with his description, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This imagery highlights the environmental devastation and the callous disregard for all life forms affected by the factories. The owners and managers also prioritize profits over their employees' welfare, subjecting them to grueling work conditions without any concern for their well-being or safety. They exploit their workers, often firing them without notice or compensation, as there were few regulations or protections for labor in that era. Sinclair's portrayal of the workers as "slaves" underscores the inhuman treatment they endured, with no recourse or support systems in place. Even when unions were formed, they often worsened the situation by exploiting the workers themselves. The unchecked power of the owners and managers, combined with the desperation of the workers, resulted in a system that was as oppressive and exploitative as chattel slavery.

Many authors employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes towards significant topics. Some techniques work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes many of these methods in his novel "The Great Gatsby." One approach he often uses is combining an adjective and a noun that don't typically go together to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Another technique is investing meaning in symbols and using them repeatedly for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs the latter technique with several colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel, Fitzgerald assigns meanings to colors like white/gray and red/pink, and later uses these meanings to reinforce a particular feeling around important objects.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher, more refined status, and gray signifying age and decay. He establishes this meaning early in the novel by frequently using both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as “in white” (8), and even Nick wears “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party. Tom is in a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). The only time people aren’t wearing white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald also uses these colors to depict common, unimportant subjects: as Nick heads to work, he descends “the white chasms of lower New York” (56), and the names of people at Gatsby’s parties become “gray names” (61) on his schedule. Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses” (28), and plain or common people and places are described as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy shared a “white girlhood” (19), there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).

After imbuing these colors with meaning, Fitzgerald uses them to symbolize unimportance or uniformity in subjects. This technique begins with Daisy. After a long period with little significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster” (74); readers start to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform, something that Gatsby desires and yearns for. Fitzgerald employs this method often to emphasize Daisy’s uniformity, such as with a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her wearing “white” (115) before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

Another thing I've been doing is researching the land around San Diego. It's got a great climate for farming, so it's no surprise that it's super productive. You can find all sorts of stuff there like tomatoes, citrus fruits, and all sorts of greens. There's a big market for organic produce too, with many local supporters lined up. Plus, they do tours and let you enjoy the outdoors. Sounds like a sweet deal, right? But it's not all sunshine and roses. Organic farming can be pricey because you've got to put in extra work to keep things pest-free and healthy without using chemicals. And the land I found on a real estate website?
